> We think this twist on the classic spag bol is a winner! Packed with flavour and extra
> nutrients, it will have everyone in your home going back for more - better get in
> there quick!

Put a large #frying pan{} on high heat and add a splash of @oil{}. When the oil is hot add
the @British beef mince{500%g} to the pan. Break your beef up with a #spoon{} and cook for
~{5%minutes} until nicely browned all over. Season with a generous pinch of @salt{} and
@black pepper{}.

While your beef is browning, get on with the rest of your prep. Cut the @onion{2} in half
through the root. Peel and chop into ½cm cubes. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(grated)
(or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Remove the core from the @yellow pepper{2}
and cut into ½cm slices.

Once your beef is browned, add your onion and pepper to the pan and cook for another
~{5%minutes} until your onion is soft. Stir in your garlic, @dried thyme{1} and
@tomato puree{2} and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Add the @tomato passata{2}, stir well and
reduce the heat to low.

Dissolve the @beef stock pot{1} in @boiling water{400%ml} and add this to the pan. Bring
your sauce to the boil and then lower the heat. Leave to simmer away for ~{20%minutes}.
The sauce will reduce and thicken in this time - this is your ragout!

Pop a large #pot{} of water on to boil. Pick the leaves from the @basil{2}(leaves picked)
and keep to one side. Chop your basil stalks as small as you can and add these to your
ragout.

When your water comes to the boil, add a generous pinch of @salt{} and the
@rigatoni pasta{400%g} and cook for ~{11%minutes} or until it is 'al dente'.

> Tip: 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness
> left in the middle.

While your pasta cooks, prepare your salsa. Chop the @black olives{60}(chopped as small
as you can) and chop the @vine tomatoes{4}(chopped into ½cm cubes). Tear in half of your
basil leaves and mix in a good glug of @oil{}. Keep to one side.

When your pasta is cooked, drain into a #colander{} (reserve a splash of the cooking
water). Return your pasta and the cooking water to the pot, off the heat and mix well.
Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} to taste. Keep to one side.

Taste your ragout and season with more @salt{} and @black pepper{} if necessary. Tear in
your remaining basil leaves. Pour your ragout into your pasta and mix well. Serve in
deep #bowls{} and sprinkle on the @grated hard Italian style cheese{80%g}, top with your
salsa and enjoy!